Band 1
第一等

Debevoise & Plimpton LLP

Debevoise & Plimpton LLP



View Profile
æŸ¥çœ‹ç®€ä»‹







From the Chambers USA guide

Basic facts about the departmentKey offices include New York and Washington, DC. 
What the team is known for In an elite category of private fund practices with a considerable global footprint and an extensive client base of top-tier private equity sponsors. Represents all manner of private equity businesses, including some of the largest debt fund managers. Noted activity in the representation of secondary funds in connection with transactions and fundraisings. 
Strengths Sources agree that Debevoise is among the true market leaders in this space: "Fantastic. I think they're the best. Their administration is excellent, they are extremely responsive and they are good communicators. When I ask for things I get them in the timeframe I've asked for. It's very good when I have a problem at the last minute."
One client reports: "They are efficient, knowledgeable and have great resources. Their strength is their balance between us and our potential investors."
Work highlights Represented Global Infrastructure Partners in connection with the $15 billion formation of Global Infrastructure Partners III. 
Assisted GSO Capital Partners, Blackstone's credit platform, regarding the formation of a $6.5 billion global mezzanine fund, GSO Capital Opportunities Fund III. 
Significant clients Oaktree Capital Management, KKR, Morgan Stanley, EIG Global Energy Partners, The Carlyle Group. 
Notable practitioners  
Rebecca Silberstein co-heads the firm's private equity practice and is widely identified as a leading figure in the market. She recently represented Kelso & Company in its formation of a $2.6 billion US buyout fund. Her extensive expertise also covers infrastructure, credit and distressed debt funds and acquisitions. Sources say: "She always understands the issues, is very commercial in her approach and understands our business and sensitivities well." 
Erica Berthou heads the firm's global investment funds practice and is dubbed a "force of nature" by one impressed source. Others express their appreciation that she is "very smart, hard-working, very commercial and willing to go the extra mile for client service." Her impressive client roster includes Oaktree Capital Management, Brookfield Asset Management and Global Infrastructure Partners. 
Jordan Murray continues to impress in the fund formation space, handling a full range of matters including fund restructurings and secondary transactions. He is highly rated by clients, one of whom describes him as "someone I can trust to handle sensitive negotiations with investors." He recently represented Tenex Capital Management in the formation of an $800 million buyout fund. 
David Schwartz has comprehensive experience in this space, advising on buyout fund formation and funds of funds, among other matters. One source remarks that he is "a very detail-oriented, very pragmatic person who provides sound advice."
Jonathan Adler has played key roles on recent matters for Crescent Capital Group and Morgan Stanley. Sources are quick to dub him "an extraordinary lawyer; he's very thoughtful and brings a commercial, get-things-resolved attitude."
Michael Harrell is a highly regarded figure and is lauded as "a dean of the industry." His wealth of experience is commented upon, as is his commercial understanding. He recently advised the American Investment Council with respect to the effects of legal developments on the global private equity industry. 

^ Return to Top



Band 1
第一等

Kirkland & Ellis LLP

Kirkland & Ellis LLP



View Profile
æŸ¥çœ‹ç®€ä»‹







From the Chambers USA guide

Basic facts about the departmentKey offices include Chicago, San Francisco and New York. 
What the team is known for Impressively deep group of private funds specialists noted for its handling of a large volume of fundraisings for prominent high-end and midmarket sponsors. A global footprint ensures that it is well equipped to take on sophisticated matters involving buyout funds and real estate funds and its influence in the latter space continues to expand. 
Strengths One interviewee explains: "The way they train their attorneys makes them more thoughtful and creative - they think about things in a way that's cutting-edge."
Another source states: "The firm is very knowledgeable, confident and committed to being a leader in the private equity industry."
Work highlights Represented Vista Equity Partners in numerous multibillion-dollar fund formations, including that of Vista Equity Partners VI, a fund with a $10 billion target. 
Represented Madison Dearborn Partners in connection with all aspects of the formation of the $4.4 billion Madison Dearborn Capital Partners Fund VII. 
Significant clients Thoma Bravo, AEA Investors, Accel-KKR, Warburg Pincus, Audax Group. 
Notable practitioners  
According to one source, John O'Neil has a "strong sense of the market and tracks it well. He is incredibly responsive, knowledgeable of negotiating positions and also has familiarity of LP and GP demands." He heads the firm's investment funds group and handles fund formations as part of a comprehensive private equity practice. 
Andrew Wright is described by sources as a "pragmatic and levelheaded guy." He recently led for Warburg Pincus in connection with the formation of Warburg Pincus Private Equity XII, a fund which significantly exceeded its $12 billion hard cap. 
Chris Kallos has a strong track record in the formation of a range of high-value funds, including buyout funds and growth equity funds. Sources attest to his "great strengths" and note that he "knows the market and knows the players very well."
Sarah Kirson demonstrates particular expertise in energy fund formation. She recently represented Pearl Energy in a $500 million fund formation and capital fundraising matter. 
Bruce Ettelson focus his practice on the structuring and formation of private equity funds and their management companies. He is frequently sought out by leading private equity firms such as Thoma Bravo. Sources state that he is "fabulous" and a "fine lawyer."
Sean Hill is thought of by one effusive source as an "absolute rock star." Others are similarly complimentary and praise him for being "very pragmatic, responsive and very attuned to his clients' particular needs." He is called upon to represent a diverse range of sponsors, including venture capital, energy and secondaries funds. 

^ Return to Top



Band 1
第一等

Simpson Thacher & Bartlett LLP

Simpson Thacher & Bartlett LLP



View Profile
æŸ¥çœ‹ç®€ä»‹







From the Chambers USA guide

Basic facts about the departmentKey office is New York. 
What the team is known for Prospering private equity practice with comprehensive expertise that spans traditional buyout funds and alternative assets, including real estate, distressed debt and credit. Unparalleled track record representing some of the largest private equity sponsors in mega fundraisings. 
Strengths Clients enthuse: "They are wonderful to work with. They're smart, efficient and creative in terms of problem solving - we couldn't be happier."
Highly satisfied sources declare: "They're exceptionally smart. They have lots of market experience which contributes to great advice, and a depth of talent that enables them to execute complex work for us in a short timeframe."
Work highlights Represented Stonepeak in the formation of the $3.5 billion Stonepeak Infrastructure Fund II. 
Continued to advise Blackstone on a number of high-profile mega fundraising activities, most recently the establishment of the $8 billion Blackstone Real Estate Partners Europe V. 
Significant clients Aquiline, CIM Group, The Carlyle Group, KKR, Lexington Partners. 
Notable practitioners  
Thomas Bell's extensive history in the area of private funds has attracted a noteworthy body of clients such as Morgan Stanley, CIM Group and Macquarie. He is able to advise on every kind of fund from hedge to real estate. 
Barrie Covit continues to enjoy an enviable reputation for his representation of market leaders such as The Carlyle Group. He is admired for his "carefully considered advice." Another source describes him as "very cerebral, but practical," and goes on to say: "I think the world of Barrie."
Michael Wolitzer wins the broad acclaim of market observers, with one interviewee describing him as "one of the top people in the market in terms of intellect, skill, understanding of the marketplace, bringing people together and getting to the finish line." He recently represented Blackstone in the formation of its $8 billion Blackstone Real Estate Partners Europe V. 
Glenn Sarno is well known for representing his clients in connection with funds relating to a number of different asset categories, including traditional private equity, real estate and mezzanine. He recently advised The Carlyle Group in connection with the establishment of the $4.2 billion Carlyle Realty Partners VII. 
Jason Herman is considered by one client to be "a particularly engaged, client-oriented lawyer. We never felt ignored; he gave us a lot of attention and focus and was very responsive." His comprehensive experience makes him a popular choice to advise on all manner of fund formations. 
Jonathan Karen has played a central role in many of the firm's most significant recent fund formations and can name entities such as Blackstone among his impressive and growing client roster. Commentators remark that he is "phenomenal - he's among the best at keeping things civil and insightful." 

^ Return to Top



Band 2
第二等

Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton LLP

Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton LLP



View Profile
æŸ¥çœ‹ç®€ä»‹







From the Chambers USA guide

Basic facts about the departmentKey office is New York. 
What the team is known for Deep expertise structuring private equity funds and alternative investment products that are offered in the USA, Europe, Asia and Latin America. Likewise proficient in counseling limited partners on their investments in private equity, hedge and real estate assets. Also noted for its advice on strategic minority investments to fund managers. 
Strengths Impressed clients state: "Cleary provides sophisticated advice and seamless coordination among its various practice areas."
Some of its key strengths are named as being "amenable to client needs, very timely, thoughtful and detail-oriented."
Work highlights Represented TPG Capital in a variety of fund formation matters, among them the formation of its seventh flagship buyout fund, which closed with approximately $10.5 billion in commitments. 
Provided counsel to Hillhouse Capital Management regarding the formation of the $4.7 billion Hillhouse Fund III. 
Significant clients The Raine Group, Northstar, JPMorgan Chase, Coller Capital, Korea Investment Corporation. 
Notable practitioners  
Managing partner Michael Gerstenzang earns commendation as a "very strategic thinker who can navigate difficult issues and bring a lot of experience to the table." He handles fund formation matters for a wide scope of private investment funds, such as venture capital, growth and infrastructure. 
Elizabeth Lenas is noted for her extensive knowledge of fund formation and her broad experience of fundraising. She receives admiration from interviewees, who dub her an "irreplaceable resource" and "someone you want on your team to get things done efficiently." She has played a pivotal role on the formation of some of TPG Capital's largest funds of the past twelve months. 

^ Return to Top



Band 2
第二等

Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver & Jacobson LLP

Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver & Jacobson LLP



View Profile
æŸ¥çœ‹ç®€ä»‹







From the Chambers USA guide

Basic facts about the departmentKey offices include New York and Washington, DC. 
What the team is known for Continues to deepen its global asset management bench and attract high-caliber sponsors in the real estate, energy, credit and buyout spaces. Able to offer its expanding client base an integrated service, working closely with its practices in tax, regulatory and employee benefits. Also noted for its strength in cross-border matters. 
Strengths One source comments: "The quality of their advice is where they stand alone. It's hard for someone else to replicate that."
One source dubs Fried Frank a "top-tier firm," and go on to say: "They are commercially astute and deliver excellent quality."
Work highlights Counseled Brookfield Asset Management in the formation of its flagship real estate fund, which had a final close of $9 billion. 
Provided assistance to Permira in the establishment of its latest flagship fund, Permira VI. 
Significant clients Goldman Sachs, BlackRock, J.P. Morgan Asset Management, Fortress Investment Group, Morgan Stanley. 
Notable practitioners  
Kenneth Rosh, head of the firm's private equity funds practice, is singled out as "spectacular when it comes to fund formation." Other clients enthuse that he is a "pleasure to work with," explaining that he is "experienced and knowledgeable, and definitely looking out for our best interests at all times." His experience covers all aspects of fund formation and he remains a leading light for the largest private equity sponsors. 
Lawrence Barshay heads the firm's asset management practice. He is a prominent figure in the area of hedge funds, but the breadth of his practice also extends to being well versed in private equity investment matters. Sources consider him to be a "top-notch" attorney and one remarks: "You can't do better!"
Impressed sources "think the world" of Richard Ansbacher, applauding his "commercially intelligent and innovative advice." He counsels major investors such as Permira in the structuring and establishment of a vast range of funds. Additionally, he advises global private equity funds in areas such as regulatory compliance and employee compensation. 

